{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"Critical","confidence":"high","title":"Stale depositor authorization lets a previous owner reclaim transferred deposited NFTs and their staking proceeds","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:228-240","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:368-374","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:651-663","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:672-745","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStakingStorage.sol:130-135"],"claim":"Deposited NFTs cache `depositor[nftId] = userAddr` when supplied to lending, and `_validOwner` trusts that cached depositor whenever it is non-zero instead of consulting the live gateway/ptoken ownership source. The owner-change stop-stake paths never clear or refresh `depositor`, and `withdraw()` later authorizes solely by `depositor` plus `staker == address(0)`. As a result, after a deposited NFT is sold, redeemed, or liquidated elsewhere in Pawnfi, the old depositor remains authorized inside ApeStaking.","impact":"A previous owner can continue claiming rewards and, once staking is stopped, withdraw the NFT itself from ApeStaking custody even though beneficial ownership has moved to someone else. This enables direct theft of both the NFT principal and associated ApeCoin proceeds from the new rightful owner.","paths":["User deposits an NFT through ApeStaking, which records `depositor[nftId]`.","The NFT's beneficial ownership changes elsewhere in the Pawnfi gateway/ptoken flow.","A stop-stake callback removes the staker but leaves `depositor[nftId]` untouched.","The old depositor calls reward or withdrawal paths and receives ApeCoin and eventually the NFT itself."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Pair withdrawals authenticate only the BAKC leg and ignore current BAYC/MAYC ownership","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:395-401","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:446-459","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:501-505"],"claim":"In `_withdrawApeCoin`, pair withdrawals validate only the BAKC side through `_validStaker(..., BAKC_ADDR, bakcTokenId, ...)`. The function never checks `_validOwner` for the paired BAYC/MAYC `mainTokenId`, even though the pair-claim path does require current main-leg ownership. This leaves pair unstake authority tied only to the BAKC leg.","impact":"An address that still controls the BAKC side but no longer owns the paired BAYC/MAYC can still withdraw the pair-staked ApeCoin principal and accrued rewards, bypassing the current main-NFT owner and depriving them of control over the pair position.","paths":["A user opens a BAYC/BAKC or MAYC/BAKC pair stake.","The BAYC/MAYC ownership changes while the BAKC side remains with the original user.","The original BAKC holder calls `withdrawApeCoin(..., _nftPairs)` using the historical `mainTokenId`.","ApeStaking authorizes the withdrawal without checking current main-leg ownership."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Partial unstake silently strands accrued ApeCoin rewards inside ApeStaking","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:404-422","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:455-463","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:528-569"],"claim":"For non-max withdrawals, `_removeUserInfo` forces `claimAmount = 0`, but ApeStaking still executes the downstream `withdrawApeCoin` / `withdrawBAKC` call against the staking adapter. Those withdraw calls send both principal and any pending rewards to `address(this)`, while `_repayAndClaim` later distributes only `totalWithdrawAmount + totalClaimAmount` based on the locally zeroed `claimAmount`. The actual reward tokens transferred during the unstake are therefore left unaccounted for inside ApeStaking.","impact":"Users who partially unstake can lose all rewards accrued by the affected NFT, with those ApeCoin balances becoming trapped in ApeStaking and no longer attributable to any user. This is direct reward loss and can accumulate into a protocol-side accounting hole.","paths":["A staked NFT accrues pending ApeCoin rewards.","The user calls `withdrawApeCoin` for less than the full staked amount.","ApeStaking zeroes `claimAmount` locally but still performs the external unstake that transfers rewards to this contract.","`_repayAndClaim` ignores those received rewards, leaving them stranded."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Reward claims follow current ownership instead of the recorded staker when ownership drift exists","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:298-310","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:368-374","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:475-518","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:672-745"],"claim":"`claimApeCoin` and `claimAndRestake` authenticate with `_validOwner` only and never require `msg.sender` / `userAddr` to equal `_nftInfo[nftAsset].staker[nftId]`. If ownership changes while ApeStaking still retains stale staking state for that NFT, the new owner can claim or restake rewards even though the old staker remains the address recorded in ApeStaking's accounting and health calculations.","impact":"Pending rewards can be redirected away from the recorded borrower/staker to the current owner, and ApeStaking's internal stake-based health accounting can remain attached to the wrong address. That creates realistic yield theft and bad-debt/liquidation distortions whenever ownership-change synchronization lags or fails.","paths":["A user stakes an NFT and ApeStaking records them as `staker`.","Ownership later changes but ApeStaking has not yet cleared or updated the staking record.","The new owner calls `claimApeCoin` or `claimAndRestake`.","ApeStaking pays or reinvests rewards for the new owner while the old staker remains in internal accounting."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-005","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Borrow and liquidation decisions use the last configured rewards range instead of the active one","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:132-139","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:148-158","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:331-335","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:604-615","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/interfaces/IApeCoinStaking.sol:60-65"],"claim":"`getRewardRatePerBlock` reads `pools(poolId).lastRewardsRangeIndex` and then fetches that `timeRange` as if it were the currently active rewards schedule. In the staking interface, however, `lastRewardsRangeIndex` is only the index of the most recently configured range stored in `timeRanges`, not necessarily the range active at the current timestamp. ApeStaking uses this value in both borrow admission and liquidation health checks.","impact":"If the latest configured range differs materially from the active range, ApeStaking can overestimate current yield and admit undercollateralized borrowing, or underestimate it and stop healthy positions. Either direction can create user loss, forced unwinds, or protocol bad debt.","paths":["A pool has multiple reward ranges configured in ApeCoinStaking.","The newest configured range is not the one active at the current time.","ApeStaking computes health or borrow eligibility from `lastRewardsRangeIndex`.","Borrowing or liquidation proceeds on a materially wrong reward-rate assumption."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Per-NFT iToken balances are floor-split, which can lock withdrawals and strand residual collateral","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:195-202","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:228-254"],"claim":"After depositing multiple NFTs, ApeStaking mints one aggregate iToken amount and assigns each NFT `singleQuantity = amount / length`, truncating any remainder. Later, each NFT withdrawal redeems only that floored per-NFT balance and requires the redeemed pTokens to satisfy `redeemAmount >= pieceCount`. The unassigned remainder is attached to no NFT, so individual NFTs can become underfunded relative to the one-NFT redemption threshold.","impact":"Users can end up with NFTs that cannot be withdrawn even though the contract still holds leftover iTokens from the original batch. This creates realistic withdrawal lockups and strands residual collateral inside ApeStaking.","paths":["A user deposits multiple NFTs in one batch.","The minted iToken amount is not exactly divisible by the NFT count.","Each NFT is assigned only the floored share, with the remainder left unattached.","A later single-NFT withdrawal redeems too little underlying and reverts on `redeemAmount >= pieceCount`."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Ignoring non-zero iToken mint error codes can strand newly deposited NFTs","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:242-254","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:194-202","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/interfaces/ITokenLending.sol:5-8"],"claim":"`ITokenLending.mint` is a cToken-style function that returns an error code, but `_depositNftToLending` ignores that return value entirely. If minting fails without reverting after the NFT has already been deposited into the pToken market, ApeStaking will continue with zero or insufficient iTokens recorded for that NFT while retaining the deposited position. Later withdrawals can only redeem via the recorded iToken balance and will fail the `redeemAmount >= pieceCount` check.","impact":"A non-reverting mint failure in the lending market can turn an apparently successful NFT deposit into an indefinitely or permanently stuck position, leaving the user unable to recover the NFT through ApeStaking's normal withdrawal flow.","paths":["The user deposits NFTs and ApeStaking deposits them into the pToken market.","`ITokenLending.mint(tokenAmount)` returns a non-zero error code instead of reverting.","ApeStaking records no usable iToken backing for the deposited NFT and the transaction still succeeds.","A later withdrawal attempt cannot redeem enough pTokens and reverts."],"round":1,"source_agents":["opencode_1"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"One ownership-mismatched NFT flips the entire withdrawal batch into redeem mode","locations":["0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:395-401","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:437-463","0x85018cf6f53c8bbd03c3137e71f4fca226cda92c/contracts/ApeStaking.sol:556-560"],"claim":"`_withdrawApeCoin` reuses a single mutable `actionType` across the whole batch. Once any NFT causes `_validStaker` to downgrade the action from `WITHDRAW` to `REDEEM`, all later NFTs in the same call are also settled under `REDEEM`, even if those later NFTs are still fully owned by the caller. Under `REDEEM`, `_repayAndClaim` forwards claim amounts to `feeTo` instead of the user.","impact":"If a batched withdrawal contains one ownership-mismatched position, rewards from other otherwise healthy NFTs in the same batch can be confiscated to `feeTo`. This amplifies any stale ownership-state issue into broader reward loss.","paths":["A user withdraws multiple NFTs in one `withdrawApeCoin` call.","At least one NFT in the batch hits the stale-state path where `_validStaker` returns `REDEEM`.","The shared `actionType` remains `REDEEM` for subsequent NFTs.","Rewards from later NFTs are paid to `feeTo` instead of the user."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1","merge_review"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Missing zero address validation for fee recipient","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an admin misconfiguration risk only. Setting `feeTo` to `address(0)` burns protocol fees but does not create a permissionless exploit or user-funds vulnerability in the audited logic."},{"title":"Potential integer overflow in exchange rate calculation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The contract is compiled with Solidity 0.8.10, so arithmetic overflow reverts automatically. This is not a live vulnerability."},{"title":"Permissionless liquidation can be triggered by anyone","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`unstakeAndRepay` is intentionally public and pays a liquidation reward. It is gated by a health check on the victim position, so this is expected protocol behavior rather than an access-control flaw."},{"title":"Unlimited ERC20 token approvals","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Granting max approvals to trusted core integrations is standard and not reportable on its own without a concrete compromise or malicious-upgrade path in scope."},{"title":"Missing input validation for NFT asset in staking","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`depositAndBorrowApeAndStake` immediately calls `_getPTokenStaking(stakingInfo.nftAsset)`, which already restricts `nftAsset` to BAYC or MAYC via `require`."},{"title":"Missing array length validation in withdraw function","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Supplying very large arrays only risks the caller's own gas usage. This is not a protocol-level vulnerability."},{"title":"Missing validation for stakingInfo borrowAmount","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Borrow sizing is already constrained by the staking-rate check in ApeStaking and by downstream `apePool.borrowBehalf` logic. The candidate does not identify a concrete bypass."},{"title":"No check for duplicate NFT IDs in deposit arrays","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Duplicate IDs would cause the second `safeTransferFrom` to fail because the caller no longer owns the NFT, reverting the transaction rather than creating exploitable incorrect accounting."},{"title":"No access control on claimAndRestake","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function does have access control: `msg.sender` must be `userAddr` or hold `REINVEST_ROLE`. The reported title is factually incorrect."},{"title":"Division by zero in getStakeInfo when poolId is invalid","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`getStakeInfo` performs no division at all. The candidate is unsupported by the source code."}]}
